, Han, Ho, Phoung, Chan.  Korean Tam, Phong, Nam, Thai, Tuong, Chung, Thach, Tinh, Manh, Tham, Uyen, Vang.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname жЁӮ, meaning вҖҳhappinessвҖҷ in Chinese: from the first element of the personal name Le Fu (жЁӮзҲ¶), style name of Yan, son of the Duke Dai of Song (ruler of the state of Song, reigned 799вҖ“766  BC ). Yan's grandson Le Ju (жЁӮиҺ’) inherited Le (жЁӮ) as his surname.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname еӢ’: (i) from the second element of the placename Shu-Le (з–ҸеӢ’), an ancient state (located in present-day Xinjiang Uyghur autonomous region) during the Western Han dynasty (206  BC вҖ“25  AD ). (ii) a surname near the Bohai Sea region during the Han dynasty (206  BC вҖ“220  AD ). (iii) a surname traced back to the Hun ethnic group in northern China during the Jin dynasty (265вҖ“420  AD )."],"variants":[{"name":"Yue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Chi, Feng, Gang, Wei, Chun, Guo, Jin, Kin, Ping, Yan, Yun, Zhang, Chau, Du, Hau, Hung, My, Sau.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname еІі (or е¶Ҫ), meaning вҖҳhigh mountainвҖҷ in Chinese: traced back to Si Yue (еӣӣеІі or еӣӣе¶Ҫ), said to be the title of an official post in charge of sacrificial rituals on the site of famous mountains during the reign of the legendary Emperor Yao (<i>c.</i> 24th century  BC ) and Emperor Shun (<i>c.</i> 23rd century  BC )."]},{"name":"Lok","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Ping, Tat, Wing, Ying Lin, Chi Ming, Ching Wah, Chun, Chung Man, Han, Kam, Kam Tim, Kin.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surname жЁӮ, see   Le   1.","Chinese: Cantonese form of the surnames йҷё, й№ҝ, йҖҜ and зҰ„, see   Lu   5 and (7-9)."]},{"name":"Li","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ming, Li, Jian, Hong, Yan, Ping, Jing, Yong, Ying, Hui, Jin, Min, Chung.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname жқҺ, meaning вҖҳplumвҖҷ: (i) said to have been adopted in place of the Chinese surname зҗҶ (also pronounced Li; meaning вҖҳrulesвҖҷ in Chinese) by Li Zhen (еҲ©иІһ), son of an official called Li Zheng (зҗҶеҫө) in the late Shang dynasty (1600вҖ“1046  BC ). It is said that Li Zhen's father incurred the displeasure of King Zhou of Shang (died 1046  BC ) and Li Zhen fled to a wasteland area, where he survived on wild plums. After his return to civilization, he changed his surname to Li (жқҺ вҖҳplumвҖҷ), a word with the same pronunciation. The original surname, зҗҶ, is said to be from Li Guan (зҗҶе®ҳ), the name of a post of officials in charge of legislation in ancient China. Li Er (жқҺиҖі), also known as Lao Tzu or Lao Zi, traditionally regarded as the founder of Taoism, is believed to have been a descendant of Li Zhen. (ii) adopted as a surname by the Chi Li (еҸұжқҺ) family from the Xianbei ethnic group during the Northern Wei dynasty (386вҖ“534  AD ). (iii) in the early years of the Tang dynasty (618вҖ“907  AD ), sixteen high officials with different surnames were granted the surname Li (жқҺ), the surname of the royal family of the Tang dynasty, by Emperor Taizong of Tang (died 649  BC ), because of their contributions to the establishment of the Tang regime. (iv) the surname can also be traced back to several minority ethnic groups in ancient China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname й»Һ, meaning вҖҳblackвҖҷ or вҖҳmultitudeвҖҷ in ancient Chinese: (i) from Li (й»Һ), the name of an ancient state (located in Changzhi in Shanxi province) during the Shang dynasty (1600вҖ“1046  BC ), which was annexed in the Western Zhou dynasty (1046вҖ“771  BC ) and later granted to Fengshu, also known as Li Hou (й»ҺдҫҜ, 'Marquis Li'). (ii) adopted as a surname by the Su Li (зҙ й»Һ) family, members of the Xianbei ethnic group, during the Northern Wei dynasty (386вҖ“534  AD )."]}]},{"name":"Bird","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names В© Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Scottish: nickname for a young or a small and slender person, from Middle English <i>brid</i>, <i>bird</i>, <i>burd</i> (Old English <i>bird</i>, <i>brid</i>, perhaps also <i>byrd</i>) вҖҳbird, young birdвҖҷ, also вҖҳyoung man, young woman, childвҖҷ.","Irish: Anglicized form of a number of Irish names erroneously thought to contain the element <i>Г©an</i> вҖҳbirdвҖҷ, in particular <i>Г“ hГүinigh</i> (see   Heagney  ), <i>Г“ hГүanna</i> (see   Heaney  ), <i>Г“ hГүanachГЎin</i> (see   Heneghan  ), and <i>Mac an DГ©aghanaigh</i> (see   McEneaney  ).","Americanized form (translation into English) of various European surnames meaning вҖҳbirdвҖҷ, as for example German and Jewish (Ashkenazic)   Vogel  , French   Loiseau  , Czech <b>PtГЎДҚek</b> (see   Ptacek  ) and <b>PtГЎk</b>, Polish   Ptak  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Kingbird","meanings":["Native American (Chippewa; also <b>King Bird</b>): translation into English of the Chippewa personal name <i>Ogimaa-bines(i)</i>, meaning literally вҖҳthe bird that is kingвҖҷ and referring to the mythological bird-like creature thunderbird. See also   Bird   4.","History: The progenitor of the large family of the Kingbirds from the Red Lake, MN, was Ogimaa-bines, a musical gifted Chippewa spiritual leader."]},{"name":"Byrd","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Heaney","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Aidan, Malachy, Nuala, Ronan.","Irish:","Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Г“ hГүanna</b> and <b>Г“ hГүinne</b>, вҖҳdescendant of <i>Гүanna</i>вҖҷ, a very common personal name of uncertain meaning. It was borne by various early Christian saints, most notably Saint Гүanna of Aran. The name has been erroneously understood as containing the element <i>Г©an</i> вҖҳbirdвҖҷ and as a result the surname was sometimes Anglicized as   Bird  ."]},{"name":"Blackbird","meanings":["Native American (also <b>Black Bird</b>): translation into English of a personal name such as Lakota Sioux <i>ZiЕӢtkala Sapa</i>, which is composed of <i>ziЕӢtkala</i> вҖҳbirdвҖҷ and <i>sapa</i> вҖҳblackвҖҷ. See also   Bird   4.","English (Durham): nickname for someone with a dark beard, from Middle English <i>blak</i> вҖҳblackвҖҷ + <i>berd</i> вҖҳbeardвҖҷ (Old English <i>blГҰc</i> + <i>beard</i>)."]},{"name":"Burd","meanings":["English: variant of   Bird  .","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): nickname for a man with a notable beard, from a southern Yiddish pronunciation of Yiddish <i>bord</i> вҖҳbeardвҖҷ."]},{"name":"Burt","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Bird  ,   Bright  , or   Burd  .","German: Middle High German <i>burt</i> вҖҳthat which is due or properвҖҷ, therefore a nickname for someone who has fulfilled his obligations properly.","Jewish (from Poland and Ukraine): variant of   Burd  ."]},{"name":"Hummingbird","meanings":["Native American (Cherokee): translation into English of a personal name based on the Cherokee name <i>walela</i> for a hummingbird. See also   Bird   4."]},{"name":"Heagney","meanings":["Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Г“ hГүignigh</b>, вҖҳdescendant of <i>Гүigneach</i>вҖҷ, a personal name meaning вҖҳforcefulвҖҷ. The spelling of the Irish name was often simplified to <b>Г“ hГүinigh</b> and then Anglicized as   Heaney   or вҖҳtranslatedвҖҷ as   Bird  , the latter because of a perceived similarity to <i>Г©an</i> вҖҳbirdвҖҷ."]}]},{"name":"David","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names В© Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Biblical name, borne by the greatest of all the kings of Israel, whose history is recounted with great vividness in the first and second books of Samuel and elsewhere. As a boy he killed the giant Philistine Goliath with his slingshot. As king of Judah, and later of all Israel, he expanded the power of the Israelites and established the security of their kingdom. He was also noted as a poet, many of the Psalms being attributed to him. The Hebrew derivation of the name is uncertain; it is said by some to represent a nursery word meaning вҖҳdarlingвҖҷ. It is a very popular Jewish name, but is almost equally common among Gentiles in the English-speaking world. It is particularly common in Wales and Scotland, having been borne by the patron saint of Wales (  see  Dewi   ) and by two medieval kings of Scotland."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":5,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":14,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705189,"age":49,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":80,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705191,"age":105,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705192,"age":118,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When David Le Bird was born about 1210, in England, his father, Richard Le Bird, was 42 and his mother, Marie de Bontishall, was 42. He had at least 1 son with Elizabeth Fitzhugh. He died in Utkinton, Cheshire, England."},"et":{"about 1210вҖ“":"umbes 1210вҖ“Surnud","1210вҖ“Male":"1210вҖ“Surnud","1194вҖ“Female":"1194вҖ“Surnud","1240вҖ“1338":"1240вҖ“1338","1170вҖ“Male":"1170вҖ“Surnud","1170вҖ“Female":"1170вҖ“Surnud","1240":"1240","1194":"1194","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","from about 1205 to 1210":"umbes 1205 kuni 1210","1210":"1210","about 1210":"umbes 1210","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Utkinton, Cheshire, England":"Utkinton, Cheshire, England","England":"England","Broxton, Cheshire, England":"Broxton, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"about 1210вҖ“":"noin 1210вҖ“Kuollut","1210вҖ“Male":"1210вҖ“Kuollut","1194вҖ“Female":"1194вҖ“Kuollut","1240вҖ“1338":"1240вҖ“1338","1170вҖ“Male":"1170вҖ“Kuollut","1170вҖ“Female":"1170вҖ“Kuollut","1240":"1240","1194":"1194","1170":"1170","1290":"1290","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1224":"1224","from about 1205 to 1210":"vuodesta noin 1205 vuoteen 1210","1210":"1210","about 1210":"noin 1210","1328":"1328","1317":"1317","Utkinton, Cheshire, England":"Utkinton, Cheshire, England","England":"England","Broxton, Cheshire, England":"Broxton, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"about 1210вҖ“":"environ 1210вҖ“DГ©cГ©dГ©","1210вҖ“Male":"1210вҖ“DГ©cГ©dГ©","1194вҖ“Female":"1194вҖ“DГ©cГ©dГ©e","1240вҖ“1338":"1240вҖ“1338","1170вҖ“Male":"1170вҖ“DГ